    "lesson_id": "025",
    "trigger_word": "kiu",
    "title": "LESSON 25: RELATIVE CLAUSES",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "Relative clauses add extra information about",
          "a noun. In Esperanto, we use KIU (which,",
          "who) and KIO (what, that which).",
          "",
          "KIU - for specific nouns:",
          "",
          "La viro, kiu parolas, estas instruisto.",
          "(The man who is speaking is a teacher.)",
          "",
          "La libro, kiun mi legas, estas bona.",
          "(The book that I'm reading is good.)",
          "",
          "Notice: KIUN takes -n when it's the object",
          "of the relative clause!",
          "",
          "La homo, kiu venis, estas mia amiko.",
          "(The person who came is my friend.)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dudek kvin"
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "KIO - for general ideas or unknown things:",
          "",
          "Mi komprenas tion, kion vi diras.",
          "(I understand what you're saying.)",
          "",
          "Tio, kio okazis, estis stranga.",
          "(What happened was strange.)",
          "",
          "KEY PATTERN:",
          "tio, kio  = that which / what (subject)",
          "tion, kion = that which / what (object)",
          "",
          "PRACTICE:",
          "La domo, kiu staras tie, estas malnova.",
          "(The house that stands there is old.)",
          "",
          "Relative clauses make Esperanto expressive!"
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "026",
    "trigger_word": "videbla",
    "title": "LESSON 26: THE '-EBL-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -EBL- means \"able to be\" or",
          "\"possible.\" It turns verbs into adjectives",
          "describing what CAN be done.",
          "",
          "FROM VERB TO ADJECTIVE:",
          "manĝi   → manĝebla    = to eat → edible",
          "vidi    → videbla     = to see → visible",
          "legi    → legebla     = to read → readable",
          "kredi   → kredebla    = believe → believable",
          "kompreni→ komprenebla = understand → -able",
          "",
          "IN SENTENCES:",
          "La teksto estas facile legebla.",
          "(The text is easily readable.)",
          "",
          "NEGATIVE: ne + -ebl- = impossible",
          "nevidebla = invisible",
          "",
          "-EBL- describes potential, not certainty!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dudek ses"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "027",
    "trigger_word": "klarigi",
    "title": "LESSON 27: THE '-IG-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -IG- means \"to make\" or \"to cause",
          "to be.\" It creates causative verbs - making",
          "something happen to someone or something.",
          "",
          "ADJECTIVE → CAUSATIVE VERB:",
          "pura    → purigi      = clean → to clean",
          "granda  → grandigi    = big → to enlarge",
          "klara   → klarigi     = clear → to clarify",
          "bela    → beligi      = beautiful → beautify",
          "",
          "COMPARE -IĜ- AND -IG-:",
          "varmiĝi  = to become warm (intransitive)",
          "varmigi  = to warm something (transitive)",
          "",
          "La suno varmigas la teron.",
          "(The sun warms the earth.)",
          "",
          "-IG- puts YOU in control of the change!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dudek sep"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "028",
