    "title": "LESSON 28: THE 'GE-' PREFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The prefix GE- means \"both sexes together\"",
          "or \"mixed group.\" Very useful for talking",
          "about people collectively!",
          "",
          "FAMILY TERMS:",
          "patro    = father",
          "patrino  = mother",
          "gepatroj = parents (both together)",
          "",
          "frato    = brother",
          "fratino  = sister",
          "gefratoj = siblings (brothers and sisters)",
          "",
          "MORE EXAMPLES:",
          "gesinjoroj  = ladies and gentlemen",
          "geedzoj     = married couple",
          "gelernantoj = students (male and female)",
          "",
          "One elegant prefix for inclusive language!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dudek ok"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "029",
    "trigger_word": "estus",
    "title": "LESSON 29: CONDITIONAL MOOD",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The conditional mood (-us) expresses \"would\"",
          "or hypothetical situations. It's used for",
          "polite requests and imaginary scenarios.",
          "",
          "FORMING THE CONDITIONAL:",
          "Replace the tense ending with -us:",
          "estas → estus     (is → would be)",
          "havas → havus     (has → would have)",
          "iras  → irus      (goes → would go)",
          "",
          "POLITE REQUESTS:",
          "Mi volus kafon.   = I would like coffee.",
          "Ĉu vi povus helpi? = Could you help?",
          "",
          "HYPOTHETICAL:",
          "Se mi estus riĉa, mi vojaĝus.",
          "(If I were rich, I would travel.)",
          "",
          "One simple ending for all conditional uses!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono dudek naŭ"
      }
    ]
  }
]
